Godwin's Law? Yes. It's been gone since around 2008. Now we have Poe's Law: in an era where Internet access is nearly universal, and there are few barriers to entry, either financial or intellectual, so many genuinely mentally ill people have Internet access that it has become impossible to distinguish between parody and genuine insanity with any certainty.

There was a time when the Internet was a secret club for .mil types and STEM majors, and you had to have your shit together, in terms of your capacity for abstract reasoning, to figure out how to navigate a UNIX or VMS command line interface with no one there to spoonfeed you, to get online at all.

September of 1993, it is generally agreed, was the time when personal computers running Windows 3.1, with dialup modems and a web browser called Mosaic, became a fad in the US, first among wealthy families, then the middle class, now even the methbillies and ghetto trash have smartphones and broadband access.

The influx of mouthbreathers that took place that fall was called by many the September that Never Ended. Previously, every September, a new crop of college kids would enroll. Eighteen-year-old n00bs would get online for the first time, and inevitably some of them would say or do dumb shit that annoyed the existing userbase, and get a rough education, some of it online, some of it in person from their professors and the college's sysadmins. Either they'd give up on the Internet or they'd figure out what they'd done wrong and strive to correct their behavior.

With AOL all that went out the window. WebTV in 1996 brought in millions of semiliterate bored trailer dwellers who typed in ALL CAPS and made the AOL mouthbreathers look like brilliant intellects by comparison. And now every crackhead's got a smartphone. Every time more people get on the Internet, it gets worse. You think shit's bad now? Wait five years, and these will be the Good Old Days.
